i also think they need a way to solve sets becoming less important as things go on - but that isn't hugely integral, it's a player style thing. they could change things up if they made an effort and gage says they are

prog season 2: I like the changes - the loser's ban is important. however i think the banning system is still too slow and favors the winner - no one wants to wait 3 eps before they can ban heavy storm or something. there should be a weird loser wheel in addition to the pity pack

history of ygo: this is fine but if they use the wheel again i think they really need a ref who checks if they're doing a mirror match and tells one of them at random to switch or to use another deck they rolled. there were SO MANY mirror matches. same for hist of jank

the best sealed showdown idea was letting you play fusion materials to make the fusions you pull - i think that if they continue this with synchros it'll be a great idea. we don't want an hour of a set that's boring where no one can play the set themes

playing a prog series with rotation has shown me that 5ds is where this gets reslly scary - you just can't reliably synchro because every set has some fucked up battle trap thst insta ruins it. they'll also find it hard to summon anything even if they pull it... unless

sealed showdown: when it's good it's good, when bad tis unwatchable. i think some sets should be combined with other sets, like duelist packs which tend to be kind of mid or bad eps. ygo just doesnt reprint certain interaction enough, especially spell trap removal

bc they kinda ultimately represent one of those "cruel rational ingenuity with no respect for honor or old pacts" type designs. and also the mech knight stuff in general is cool anyway so they're the most curious mixture of it

i also like that the stealth cloak forms look kind of dorky but vaguely practical too - their big thing is a single arm reaching out to attack. the single central camera eye that can cloak is a cool aspect of it as well. it's very neat and "unfair" feeling over all

alchemists were really obsessed with mercury, and the way they're such a strange non-standard design whose structure falls apart when their pilot dies adds to that "tricky new advancement that works perfectly if everything is carefully balanced" energy

they're supposed to be a weird combination of industrial european themes with the magical aspects of gaea, and i think a grest way to make them feel unique was making their entire structure revolve around liquid metal. it makes them really feel "alchemical", you know?

honestly the alseides are an all time favorite mecha design - like, the knight shaped form isn't particularly impressive but the liquid metal component and their weird arm nozzles really give them a unique touch

that said, looking at it again, i like that dilandau is taking things pretty decently in stride UNTIL HE'S ABLE TO HIT THEM WHILE THEY'RE INVISIBLE and that's when he starts freaking the fuck out. still the stay away useless miss fire that scratches his cheek is SO good

but that all added up, stupid attacks where everyone dies are an important part of military histoey, they're relying on tactics van wasn't able to beat before, and as a scene it's fucking raw as hell - so still, 10/10. love van getting the fucked up facial expressions this time

and i don't think it's ever discussed how the pilots actually control the liquid metal - with it being so freeform it's probably extremely difficult to master when trying to do weird stuff. so i could def see them being very regimented about how they use it

i don't think their alseides have a radar equivalent and it sounds like they're having to coordinate entirely with radio. i suppose it's also worth noting esca can turn into dragon form and escape straight up if it's truly boxed in

i think though that you might be able to reason it away with smth like
1. they need the direct attackers because they can't stay back and snipe or they'll be singled out and overpowered
2. they're afraid of friendly fire (a serious concern in such a scenario)
van is good at blocking or avoiding their ranged attacks during the times they try them, but it's usually one guy attacking at once - he has to parry with his sword, and there were like 15 of them

zenmetsuing so bad after dilandau orders them into their stealth cloaks is understandable - they have to act  a specific way when cloaked and the fact he CAN SEE THEM NOW makes them panicking and failing miserably unsurprising they're just not trained for that

i have to say though, as much as i love the fucked up fight scene where they just kinda get bowled over by sheer force, i think they fucked up their tactics a bit. they really should have relied more on their range advantage

interestingly though there are still majorly pressing points in this field we paper over as a society - war justifications, "culture wars"/"think of the children", chosen people narratives, the rights of lawbreakers and what it means to "respect" law, et cetera et cetera

now you might day "well duh those are obviously part of it" or "well all of those exist in older forme" and sure but my point is that i think some things are more directly part of colonialism's self justification than others and thus aptly deserve the title

i suppose for sake of argument i must bring up some concepts i think are actually colonial in opposition. id say might makes right, social darwinism, 19th century racial "science", terra nullius, lebensraum - these are good clear cut comparisons of stuff that's hard to separate

and at the end of the day it's a semantic and pointless argument anyway, just thinking sbout classic opinion "speedrunning is inherently colonial" floating by and making me go ?????

which i feel strongly abt because i PERSONALLY find the "all stories are conflict" viewpoint silly since it redefines conflict to the point of uselessness in my eyes. but i think "its colonial" weasels out of really bothering to discuss it

in case you're wondering the inspiration here was "the western view of stories as being abt conflict is colonial" which rubs me the wrong way bc while it can fit a colonial schema and was sometimes thus used it's not actually inherently so or even mostly seen that way

you end up with shit like "if you aren't religious you're a traitor who supports the oppressor" lol. it's just like at sole point i feel we need to stop using it as a weasel word target and discuss what we're directly discussing

this gets especially awkward when we force it into a binary as we so often do - the nativist spiritualists vs the rational invaders - esp since it gets so tropey that it loses sight of being applicable to real scenarios in the first place. etc

for example, i think calling "obsession with rationality" as an ideal inherently colonial is a bit silly - it was certainly a part of colonial europe but it on its own is just a concept and viewpoint that can be applied in many ways and discussed from different angles

some ideas are truly integral parts of the "colonial mind" and other ideas are merely things colonization can utilize - if you had to avoid every single concept someone evil espoused once you would very quickly have to cease existing

i think it's easy to call a concept that's popular in "the west" "colonial" to criticize it but there's kind of circular logic there too in some cases. one could argue that all european culture present is colonial in the context of once-colonized nations, it gets a little empty

8. I was really into webcomics for a while, and I keep meaning to go back and reread TRIANGLE AND ROBERT (a comic i first read when ppl were like "it's finally ended...") . it has so many baffling ideas and never needs to worry about being able to draw anything.

It was one of those series where as a kid I wasn't really prepared for its ending, so I need to go back and reread that to collect my thoughts on it imo.

Also, oh god, ASoUE does the Visual Novel thing where it just starts infodumping trivia on you. LMAOOOOOO

Some of the recurring jokes like Count Olaf always being extremely obvious and no one every believing them about who was him in disguise were extremely good too. Playing it straight while parodying it. I liked his weird relationship with the lady from the... fifth book? too

One of my favorite random surreal ideas from it was the lumbermill where they were paid in coupons, because it was funny in a mathematical sort of way. Like, technically you're getting that correct amount of value, aren't you? But ofc in reality that amount is totally unusable

7. It's been a decade so I haven't reread it to test whether it's still worth it, but I was, of course, an S Series of Unfortunate Events child. I feel that this is pretty obvious about me but I thought I might as well say. It was a very odd series indeed, wouldn't you say?

It's just a great show when you're in the mood for it. And it also despite its realism aspects just randomly is like "fuck it, monster episode" like TWICE.

The way the X-10 experimental Labor moves has inspired me for decades and I want to make smth like it some day

Nagumo and Gohto are also wonderful characters. I really like Nagumo's ties to the military lady, and Gohto's like... he's so hard to describe? He has that bureaucrat who's constantly thinking energy... bit of a planner who obscures it, but seems/is happy go lucky guy

Clancy is the only "cool american police officer" character with rights. Overall I like that it's a police procedural inspired show without being like particualrly hateful or uncomfy too. Bud is a great rival  character for the series, the Griffon is so fucked up and cool

Noa in particular is a really fun and cool protag lady. She has a kind of romance thing going on with Asuma but it doesn't hit the same annoying kinda sexist tropes a lot of shows fall into so it feels a bit reserved and I like that a lot. She just likes her robot

There's a good contrast between dramatic mecha eps and then also stuff like "the episode where everyone's going fucking nuts because they ran out of food and desperately raids local conbinis". It's just neat I think

Most people in my wheelhouse know Patlabor because of the second movie, which is this hardcore political thriller only mildly in the style of the series. As it is it's a bit more traditional, but it has a lot of really fun bits and is def willing to play w/ its limitations

The PLabor show is part of this sort of... I guess, not noir-y but, like, adult drama lineage... where it has a lot of quiet conversations and stuff. But it also has giant mecha scenes and really weird designs and lots of moments I enjoy a lot

Patlabor is pretty interesting because it's a sort of realistic ish mech show, so it's the sort of thing my parents enjoyed. One of my favorite aspects of it is that, as someone who usually likes exaggerated fantastical stuff, the show worked with mostly human characters

6. I also just really really like Patlabor. In case you haven't figured this out as a kid my parents watched a lot of old anime and it imprinted on me extremely strongly, like Nadia and my eye and ancient ruins and masks obsession lol

you can have "jeff_happy.png" and "jeff_angry.png" be stored in the images folder, and just call them like "show jeff happy" "show jeff angry" and it'll work. without this you'd need "jeff happy.png" in the uppermost folder

if you stick stuff in the images folder and then apply the top line, it'll get confused and think the images are tagged "images" and everything else is an attribute, which you DONT want, itll only let you show 1 image and hide the others. so we strip out "images"

so what if you don't want to put them in your uppermost folder, and instead want to put them in the provided images folder? what if you want to use underscores in the filenames instead of spaces because you're used to that? well these two config lines cover that

essentially, ren'py supposedly supports the ability to let you have, say, images named "jeff happy.png" "jeff angry.png" and then switch between jeff emotions without having to hide them b/c itll auto-hide the previous if changing a jeff image. BUT... you have to put them in main

today's ren'py discovery for me to share! ever been irritated at trying to get ren'py to find files properly? well with this you can just call characters directly out of the images folder instead of having to put the images in the topmost folder https://t.co/bl9SLVeTsP

A body that is kept in excellent health may be healed (have its flaws constantly repaired past normal limits) or raised (preserved like a corpse in a state of function, without need for actual living tissue). Each has advantages amd disadvantages. Et cetera.

My personal opinion is that "true" Necromancy is spirit calling (deceased human variation) and everything else related to it is arguably best considered parts of other fields. At the end of the day, it is best to be more specific when handling individual schools, though.

Particularly amusing is seeing Necromancy as inherently entropic, or about turning a body into that of death. Obviously some knowledge of the field can be used for such things. But it is by its fundamental nature anti-entropic, and thus, unnatural.  Hence it usually is "fake"

Even the art of binding a spirit to an object or body is consideres holy at times - what of go-shintai, or perhaps the ancient art of sealing an enraged spirit away? Even exorcism is arguably a form of Necromancy seen in a positive light

One could indeed say that what ultimately is seen as the core ideal of Necromancy is acting unnaturally - moving souls from their correct realm, forcing the inanimate to once again move - but this is fundamentally not particularly different than most magical arts are

The other integral half of Necromancy, spirit-calling, is such a wide-ranging and divided field that most separation is about respect. Call back the souls of ancestors and one may be called either an Honored Shaman or an accursed wretch tormenting the dead

As such, Necromancy's physical aspects are really not that much different from traditional golem  summoning. A zombie-raiser is only somewhat different in that they tend to utilize the original "form memory" of movement, and life energy as a power source.

Necromancy DOES differ from healing. Healing seeks to reform the physical or spiritual body, and perhaps to exaggerate its natural state. Necromancy on the other hand seeks to chain or recall the soul, and to forge a new stable form out of the remnant corpus.

Actually kind of serious though. Necromancy isn't a magic school. It's a combination of magical schools whose title is assigned to it when people fear or are disgusted by it conceptually. It's not even really just "reviving the dead", which is complex

but razor boomerang does have an interesting side feature, which is that in limited it offers sneaky reach for destroying blockers / utility creatures. this still doesn't make it good, but it still shows how even bad tools can do unique things. being colorless is also a plus
you also spend 5 mana up front for no value whatsoever - its only value is theoretically doing damage eventually, or being an equipment to turn things on (in which case at 3 cmc it sucks horribly)

part of razor boomerang's issue is that the creature has to tap to use it: this means you can't just win with it and infinite mana, you need infinite creatures, turns, or untaps as well. as such, it's a very hard card to make infinites with

razor boomerang is an interesting example: its rate is bad. it has theoretical applications with certain bad suppport cards. and it can't win alone. however, what it can do is win over 20 turns so long as you have a tappable creature and 5 mana. its still terrible though https://t.co/7qQkPKCeKz

when discussing 'worst cards' there's basically a simple checklist that exists in my head. one of them is
- suppose i have exclusively this card and we both have a deck of infinite basic lands otherwise. can i win with this card alone? how fast?
the limited reach check

so i guess what i'm saying is, if your card does something theoretically huge in the right situation with just one other card, i can't really see it as truly a worst card. worst cards need multi card set ups to even be considered to be doing anything, or are bad sideboard cards https://t.co/P44H5UJyVZ
